<title>
Mesenchymal stem cells lack efficacy in the treatment of experimental autoimmune neuritis despite in vitro inhibition of T-cell proliferation.
</title>

<text>

<sections.0>
Introduction
herapeutic efficacy of early administration of high dose of bone marrow-derived mesenchymal stem cells (-s) has been reported in the treatment of mouse experimental autoimmune encephalomyelitis (), a model of multiple sclerosis () [1], [2]. linical trials based upon the data are now underway in patients with  [3], [4]. revious studies suggested that these and other types of stem cells ameliorate autoimmune-mediated demyelination in the  through regulation of the inflammatory response [2], [5]. hese findings raise an important question as to whether -s might be beneficial in other inflammatory demyelinating diseases, such as uillain-arr. Γ© syndrome (GBS) and chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy (CIDP). Here, we tested whether intravenously delivered BM-MSCs were therapeutically beneficial in experimental autoimmune neuritis (EAN), an autoimmune peripheral neuropathy that has served as a model for GBS and CIDP [6], [7].
