Discussion
revious reports have demonstrated a striking therapeutic efficacy of -s when delivered early in the time course of  in mice [1], [2]. y contrast, we have shown that rat and human -s, delivered intravenously at a similar time, do not lead to any discernable neurological, neurophysiological or histopathological improvement of  in ewis rats, despite their mesenchymal potential and ability to inhibit -cell proliferation in vitro.
t is unclear why rodent and human -s have profound efficacy in  but lack any effect in  when delivered at a similar stage of disease. hese findings may reflect interspecies differences in immune response to antigen and also the distinct nature of the respective antigens between central () and peripheral () nervous system components [1], [7]. t is thus possible that the immunomodulatory effect of -s is specific to mouse  while lacking efficacy in other autoimmune neurological disorders with similar immunopathogenesis but different target antigens. nother explanation for the discrepancy between the effect of -s in  in mice and  in rat, is the difference in cell doses used in the studies. e have used cell doses (per kg) at the lower end of those used in murine  studies. n published  and  trials the cell dosage is at least one order of magnitude higher than doses used routinely in clinical practice in humans [1], [2], [12], [13]. n the case of both rodent and human studies, an upper limit of cell dosage is placed by the limits of timing of culture and cellular load that can be safely delivered without adverse effects [13].
